26 2021-01-10 nausea, diarrhea Initially, around 1500hrs on Monday, January 4th, roughly 40 minutes after the injection, I develope... Read more
Close
Initially, around 1500hrs on Monday, January 4th, roughly 40 minutes after the injection, I developed a scratchy throat, a headache, and nausea. I got home from work, and having no appetite due to nausea, I fell asleep on the couch around 1800hrs. Severe fatigue had set in. I did not wake up until 0500hrs the next morning to go to work on January 5th. I felt like I had not slept at all, however the scratchy throat had gone away. I worked all day with the nausea and headache. Throughout the day I developed chills, cold sweats, diarrhea, fever, and I felt like my mind was foggy (I had felt feverish since Monday night, but Tuesday was the first time I took my temperature that showed I had a fever.) I went home that night and slept all evening and well into the next morning. On the morning of Wednesday, January 6th, my symptoms had again gotten worse, so I called my primary care physician. He fit me in and tested me for the flu and for COVID. He prescribed me Ibuprofen for the headache/fever, and Ondansetron for the nausea/vomiting. My flu test came back negative on Thursday, January 7th, and my COVID test came back negative on Friday, January 8th. The fever finally broke on Friday evening and Saturday, January 9th was the first day I woke up without a fever. I still have the headache as of today, January 11th, and a low grade fever has returned. I am still very fatigued as well.

26 2021-04-17 vomiting, nausea 3/31/21 26YM admit with Acute issue: myocarditis, chest pain, extreme fatigue, body aches, SOB; Mode... Read more
Close
3/31/21 26YM admit with Acute issue: myocarditis, chest pain, extreme fatigue, body aches, SOB; Moderna (first dose on 3/28). No known prior COVID. Patient admits that approximately a month and a half ago, he was drinking a significant amount of alcohol with a 24-pack of beer daily and 5 drinks at night. He quit this approximately 2 weeks ago when he got back together with his girlfriend. He has had stress in his life with the death of a cousin approximately 2 weeks ago. The patient had been feeling well over the last week or so and received the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 3/28 Sunday. This was his first dose. Approximately an hour and a half after receiving the vaccine, he had symptoms of feeling dizzy with position change. He went home from work. He developed fevers, chills, rigors, diaphoresis, and headaches. He slept a lot due to these symptoms. On 3/30 Tuesday, he woke with mild chest discomfort that he described as a pressure sensation in his anterior chest. He states that it was bothersome, but not too significant. He woke up 3/31 at approximately 0200 hours with a stabbing left anterior chest discomfort. He notes that it felt like a hot knife stabbing him. He admits that over the last couple of days, he had a cough when he would lay back in bed. He admits to feeling more short of breath when flat and feeling like he had to put pillows behind his head. He came to the emergency department due to these symptoms. He was given a dose of acetaminophen and promptly had nausea and vomiting. He received a dose of aspirin 325 mg and states that his symptoms resolved shortly after that. 3/31 He now feels well and denies any further chest discomfort. He denies any dyspnea.

Pt. received his second dose Moderna Vaccine and shortly after he stated that he felt tingling and tightness in the throat and neck with warm sensation around neck. Pt also verbalized difficulty swallowing. NP?s assisted patient and assessed Pt status. Pt remained in ER observation for further monitoring and safety precautions. Pt denied any reactions to prior vaccine (first dose Moderna). Pt given hydration and was able to drink 8oz of fluid without any difficulty. Pt remained alert and oriented x3 and coherent, his initial v/s were 117/78 pulse 72, 129/81 P 76, o2 sat 99% room air. NP administered 25 mg Benadryl PO and Pt was observed for an additional 30 mins. Pt verbalized that he felt better and the sensation subsided. Once Pt was stable, and verbalized no further complaints of symptoms, he was discharged from ER observation into a taxi.

Roughly 15 hours after receiving the vaccine, I started to develop muscle aches. Within 30 minutes of the aches, they became severe. Aches were primarily located in the lower back, shoulders, hips, and calves. 30 minutes following, I started to feel very fatigued and had labored breathing. Another 1.5 later, I developed chills and had flu like symptoms. By the afternoon, I had broken into a fever and had mild nausea. Besides the muscle aches, as one symptom onset, the others seemed to fade away. By 5:00 in the evening, (roughly 25 hours after receipt of vaccine) the symptoms quickly subsided. The only residual side-effects within the rest of a 48 hour period were soreness in the area of the injection, and mild headache.

The patient presented 2 days after receiving the 2nd Moderna Vaccine with worsening acute onset right-sided lower chest pain and right upper quadrant abdominal pain associated with shortness of breath. CT pulmonary embolus protocol showed subsegmental pulmonary embolus with evidence of pulmonary infarcts for which the patient was started on an anticoagulant. An echocardiogram showed a mild to moderate decrease in LV systolic function with global hypokinesis. Cardiac MRI findings were consistent with acute myopericarditis with underlying non-ischemic cardiomyopathy disproportionate to the degree of myocarditis. The patient was discharged on a beta-blocker.

27 2021-05-02 abdominal pain, appendicitis Approximately two days after receiving the second dose of the Moderna COVID 19 vaccine, I developed ... Read more
Close
Approximately two days after receiving the second dose of the Moderna COVID 19 vaccine, I developed severe acute abdominal pain, and was diagnosed with an acute appendicitis requiring emergency surgery. After the surgery was completed, I was told that, based on clinical presentation, along with onset of symptoms, the infection was more advanced than would have been expected. After surgery, I developed an ileus, a systemic infection, as well as an abscess which required a drain to be placed in my pelvis. I was inpatient in the hospital for 9 days due to these complications, and it is my belief that there is not only a correlation between receiving the second dose of the vaccine and developing this appendicitis, but a causation. Though I have not seen any reported cases, I know that there were at least seven reported cases of appendicitis with the Pfizer variant, and the technologies are very similar.

Slept and woke on 5/29/21 with mild headache, unsettled stomach, and mild anxiety. Anxiety is more manageable so far and other symptoms were somewhat improved after eating breakfast. Currently, no plans to continue taking Buspar, but will consult doctor.

Chills; Fever; Loss of consciousness x 2; GI upset; Diarrhea; Difficulty sleeping; Pallor; Stomach flu; A spontaneous report was received from a nurse concerning a 31-year-old, male patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced loss of consciousness (LOC) x 2, gastrointestinal (GI) upset, diarrhea, difficulty sleeping, pallor, stomach flu, chills and fever. The patient's medical history, as provided by the reporter, included allergy to cefaclor and hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia. Concomitant medications reported included desvenlafaxine succinate, gabapentin and dexlansoprazole. On 23 Dec 2020 at 11:30 am, approximately six hours prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 025J20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On the morning of 23 Dec 2020, prior to receiving mRNA-1273, the patient felt "achy". At 5:30 pm, the patient experienced chills, fever to 102, GI upset and diarrhea. At 11:00 pm, the patient reported difficulty sleeping, GI upset, LOC x 2 and pallor. The patient was transported to the emergency room via ambulance. A COVID-19 polymerase chain reaction test and routine labs were collected; however, results were not provided. Treatment for the events included paracetamol, unspecified intravenous (IV) medications, ondansetron and ketorolac tromethamine. The emergency room discharge diagnosis was stomach flu. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The events, loss of consciousness (LOC) x 2, GI upset, diarrhea, difficulty sleeping, pallor, stomach flu, chills and fever, were considered resolved on 24 Dec 2020.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 31-year-old, male subject with a medical history of hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia, who experienced the unexpected events of loss of consciousness (LOC) x 2, gastrointestinal (GI) upset, diarrhea, difficulty sleeping, pallor, and stomach flu, and the expected events of chills and fever. The events of chills, fever occurred approximately 6 hrs. and the events of GI upset, loss of consciousness, difficulty sleeping occurred after 12 hrs. after the first dose of Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine. The time to onset for the events of GI upset and diarrhea were unknown. The reporter did not provide the causality assessment for the events. Due to the temporal association between the LOC and the administration of the vaccine, a causal relationship cannot be excluded, however, the subject's medical history of hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia and other concurrent conditions of GI upset, diarrhea, and stomach flu remain as confounders.

32 2021-05-01 nausea I received my second Moderna vaccine at 10:00am on 4/13, 28 days after my first one. On Fri, 4/16 at... Read more
Close
I received my second Moderna vaccine at 10:00am on 4/13, 28 days after my first one. On Fri, 4/16 at 4:00am, I woke up to use the restroom and voided my bladder. Shortly thereafter, I felt very nauseous and cold clammy. I had a sip of water, than sat down next the toilet since I thought I had food poisoning and needed to throw up. Instead, I passed out and fell from a sitting position against the wall. I woke up a few seconds later, to find my right ear cut and with quite a bit of blood (not sure what I cut it on, maybe my own thumb nail?). I stood up and walked to the sink, so I could bleed over it while apply pressure so I wouldn't make a mess. My wife had woken up at this point, and shortly after I got to the sink, I passed out again while standing (fortunately she caught me) and started twitching for a few seconds before coming to (I came to while still standing up). At this point, my wife drove me to the emergency room and we were admitted. In the ER from 4:15am-7am, they did a CT scan on my head without contracts, blood work, and an EKG. All three tests came back normal and I was diagnosed with vasovagal syncope. I have no history of any prior vasovagal event. At the ER they also sewed my ear up with 6 dissolvable stitches, gave me a big of IV fluids, a tetanus shot, and then sent me on my way, discharging me at 7:00am on 4/16. I then saw my primary care doctor that afternoon at 1:00pm on 4/16 who reviewed by medical records/test results from the ER, concurred with their vasovagal syncope diagnosis, checked my stitches, and said I could go back to normal activity largely unrestricted. I haven't had any issues since; so not overly concerned (other than the >$2,500 of ER hospital bills that are piling up), but just reporting this so you have the data.

The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown) was unknown. On 04/25/21 at 12:30pm, patient received first dose of Moderna Vaccine. Patient was clear-headed and alert, but appeared anxious at the time of receiving the vaccine. 15 minutespost vaccination, patient suddenly fainted to ground within pharmacist?s sight. RPh on duty immediately ran to patient and called for help. Patient remained laying down, until he was able to open his eyes and safely sit up. RPh on duty and front end managers were at the scene, patient was provided with water and offered 911/ambulance for help. Patient denied, stating he "is fine" and wanted to sit down before deciding before calling 911. Per pt, he didn?t think he hit his head when he fainted, but he fell on the side of his temple. RPH on duty observed patient for another 30 minutes until 1:15PM. Per patient, he only had a small breakfast and a kombucha in the morning. He also has history of fainting/anxiousness from vaccine about 20 years ago, and another fainting history while he was taking an exam. Patient mentioned he was very anxious prior to receiving the shot. Patient doesn't have any medical history and is not taking any medications or other illicit drugs. Patient lives by himself so he doesn't have anyone to watch over him when he goes home and at 1:15PM. Patient stated he still feels dizzy, nausea, and arm tingling. Front end manager called 911/Ambulance, medics arrived around 1:20PM. blood glucose, blood pressure, pulse and oxygen were checked. Medics also checked patient?s memory (asked what day it was, what year, who the president is, etc). Medics told patient that he can decide the following options: 1: to have family/friend to come pick him up and take him home OR 2: they can take him to nearby hospital for checkup. Patient lives alone so he decided to go to the hospital to have check up to "make him feel better". Patient was transported to the hospital around 1:37 PM. Both RPh on duty and front end managers were at the scene the whole time. Patient seemed to be in full command of his faculties and was following instructions at time of departure. Prior to leaving the premise, patient was advised to have someone accompany him at next dose appointment by RPh on duty. Caring call was made around 9:20AM the next day 4/26/2021. LM was left and wait for patient response. Store Director and Pharmacy Manager were notified. Pharmacy District Manager was called for alternative administration options for second dose.

Maybe 1 minute after receiving the vaccine I began to have a syncopal episode, the nurse practitioner thought that since I was heavy I began to have a vasovagal reaction. From there they asked me to sit with the others waiting 15 minutes to make sure they were ok to leave. As I sat the symptoms would come and go, as if in a pattern, and then return. The longer I sat there the more the symptoms began to grow, after sitting for an hour they decided to send me to the ER. At this time I was experiencing nausea, vomiting, sweating, I was itchy, I could not stop coughing, it was difficult to breath, and I had the worse headache. When I got to the ER they gave me drugs to reverse the allergic reaction and told me they would watch me for a while. In the next 4 hours all of the symptoms started again and I had to get another round of the reaction drugs, I ended up going through this process 4 times before I was safe enough to go home the next day. The provider that saw me and admitted me did not do any blood work or labs, they simply provided me with the reaction drugs when needed and my home medications.

This spontaneous case was reported by an other (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of PYREXIA (fever), DECREASED APPETITE (poor appettie) and FATIGUE (extreme fatigue) in a 35-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. Co-suspect product included non-company product MACITENTAN (OPSUMIT) for Pulmonary hypertension. Concurrent medical conditions included Pulmonary hypertension (secondary Pulmonary hypertension). Concomitant products included RIOCIGUAT (ADEMPAS) and APIXABAN (ELIQUIS) for an unknown indication. On 12-Apr-2021, the patient received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) 1 dosage form and MACITENTAN (OPSUMIT) (Oral) at an unspecified dose. On 12-Apr-2021, the patient experienced PYREXIA (fever) (seriousness criterion hospitalization prolonged), DECREASED APPETITE (poor appettie) (seriousness criterion hospitalization prolonged) and FATIGUE (extreme fatigue) (seriousness criterion hospitalization prolonged). The patient was hospitalized from 12-Apr-2021 to 19-Apr-2021 due to DECREASED APPETITE, FATIGUE and PYREXIA. At the time of the report, PYREXIA (fever), DECREASED APPETITE (poor appettie) and FATIGUE (extreme fatigue) outcome was unknown. No treatment medications provided by the reporter. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

35 2021-06-28 nausea Three weeks after receiving the first dose (on 02/01/2021) I woke up with extreme dizziness and imba... Read more
Close
Three weeks after receiving the first dose (on 02/01/2021) I woke up with extreme dizziness and imbalance, I felt as if I was constantly leaning to the right. I would get extremely nauseous from walking, working, or just sitting and turning my head. When I would lay down on my right side I felt as if fluid were building up and that something was going to pop. Advil, caffeine, and alcohol made my symptoms worse. I was able to find some relief by laying down on my left side and through sleep. After a week, I went to see Dr. at Clinic. They were unable to figure my issue, but they ruled out BPPV. They also did a blood and urine test at this time. After two weeks the dizziness started to fade a little, but I was left with headaches, imbalance, tiredness, and pressure behind my ear and eye. I noticed that any kind of stress or anger would make the symptoms much worse. I visited Dr. at ENT Clinic. She did several tests and was unable to find any obvious cases of my symptoms. She suggested I might have had migraines, even though I had no history of them. She told me to give it a month and come back if I was still having problems. After one Month the dizziness was pretty much gone, but I still was experiencing imbalance, headaches, and pressure. Instead of getting dizzy I would get sharp shooting headaches that would last a couple of seconds. I still had what felt like pressure behind my eye and ear. I also still was unable to lay on my right side. I visited ENT Dr. again and we decided to do an MRI with contrast. The MRI came back negative. We decided to start me on vestibular physical therapy. After 3 months I have gotten to the point where I do not feel imbalance every day. I still will have days where I feel like I am leaning to the right, but those are getting less frequent. I still occasionally get headaches, tightness, and fullness in the area. I would say I am about 75 percent better. I feel what happened in my head is somehow the same reaction I had in my left arm. I reported this reaction in a different report. I would like to point out that both times these reactions occurred I drank alcohol the night before.

Felt completely normal at time of injection, and for several hours afterward. Began feeling pain and soreness at injection site around 11PM. Felt overall coldness and increased soreness at injection site when retiring to bed at 11:30PM. Experienced extremely vivid dreams prior to awaking at ~4AM with the need to urinate. Felt normal when walking to bathroom and while urinating, no straining or abnormal effort required. Upon nearing completion of emptying bladder, ears began increasing intensity of ringing, followed immediately by cascading sensation of weakness. Realizing I was probably rapidly losing consciousness, I grabbed sink for support, in order to get as close to the ground as possible. Regained consciousness an unknown period of time later, though believed I was in bed. Upon noticing how cold my "bedsheets" were, I realized/remembered that I had lost consciousness. Felt completely weak and rested on floor for 30(?) minutes; attempts to move to a more veertical position were met with vague sensations of nausea. Eventually felt strong enough to drag myself to a nearby couch, where I slept on and off until 11:30AM, and gradually woke up to eat breakfast. I have experienced 1-2 episodes of syncope in my lifetime, and this instance aligns with how I felt at those times. Have never experienced micturition syncope at any point before, though.

It infuriates me that this side effect was dismissed as me having anxiety because I was nervous that my face was going numb which would be a natural reaction for anyone.

38 2021-02-06 indigestion Eleven days after the vaccination the patient developed 2 days of heartburn followed by a worsening ... Read more
Close
Eleven days after the vaccination the patient developed 2 days of heartburn followed by a worsening nonproductive cough, substernal chest pain, diaphoresis, palpitations, and an episode of near syncope. These worsened over about 6 days and then slowly decreased. During this time he was referred to the ED and then admitted to a civilian host nation hospital. Echocardiogram and CT scan were performed and a paericardial cyst was discovered measuring 7.4 cm. He was then referred to another facility for evasluation. The pericardial cyst was confirmed, now 6.5 cm and laboratory tests were performed on 4 FEB, but there was at that time no elevation in inflammatory markers. Cardiology and Cardiothoracic Surgery consultations were obtained, but the consultants and the attending physician (who is an infectious disease physician by training) did not think that the crescendo-decrescendo symptoms could be explained by the pericardial cyst, which was likely an incidental finding. A milder cough may have preceded these events by up to a year, and this may possibly be related to the cyst. The heartburn, chest pain, tachycardia, diaphoresis, palpitations, and near syncope may well be adverse reactions of the vaccine.

38 2021-05-03 abdominal pain upper On Friday, April 2nd, I received my first dose of the Moderna vaccine. Within minutes, my heart sta... Read more
Close
On Friday, April 2nd, I received my first dose of the Moderna vaccine. Within minutes, my heart started racing and I felt faint. Thereafter, my hands and face got the sensation of tingling. It felt like ice was running through my veins. My heart stopped racing approximately fifteen or so minutes after it began. The tingling sensation in my hands and face ended approximately one hour later. I also noticed a strange taste in my mouth during this same timeframe. Subsequently, I had the sensation of being dizzy and lightheaded. Importantly, I have never reacted to a vaccine in this manner. On Saturday, April 3rd, I woke up with symptoms that were to be expected. My arm was very sore and I felt a little achy. However, I continued to feel dizzy and lightheaded. That evening and for the next week or so, my heart was beating rapidly, and my blood pressure was elevated. I also had the continuous feeling of my skin crawling. My hands and feet also seemed to be experiencing tremors and twitching. On Sunday, April 4th, I woke up and noticed that my right eye seemed a little blurry as I read an article on my phone. I assumed I must have slept on my eye wrong and did not pay it much attention. I do not recall my eye being blurry for the rest of the day. The following morning on Monday, April 5th, I woke up once again feeling dizzy and lightheaded. As I walked to the restroom, I noticed that my right eye was blurry again. This time it seemed to be more pronounced. Moreover, when I closed my right eye, I could see hundreds of dots in different colors. In addition to having blurry vision, my legs felt weak and nearly buckled as I walked. I felt like I was intoxicated. Upon returning to bed, my teeth began chattering and I felt like I was freezing. I called my doctor?s office and spoke with a PA who recommended that I go to the ER. While I checked in at the ER, I could not remember my ZIP code. I felt like my brain was not running on all cylinders. Upon explaining my symptomology to the ER doctor, she recommended that I have my blood drawn and that I get an MRI to rule out a stroke. All test results came back normal. On Wednesday, April 7th, I made an appointment with an allergist. They tested me to see if I was allergic to Polyethylene Glycol (PEG) and Polysorbate 80. For the skin scratch portion of the test, neither of the substances had much of a reaction on my skin. I thought the Polysorbate 80 scratch had a little bit of redness to it, but it was negligible. When the doctor injected Polysorbate 80 under my skin with a syringe, a welt formed. I am not sure why, but PEG was not injected in the same manner. As a result of the test, the allergist confirmed that I am allergic to Polysorbate 80. He mentioned that there may be instances of cross reactivity to PEG for individuals that are allergic to Polysorbate 80. He recommended that I not get the second Moderna dose unless it was administered in a controlled setting. On Sunday April 11th, I noticed what felt like a hard vein in my abdominal fat. It felt slightly tender to the touch. I was fearful that it could be a clot. On Tuesday, April 13th, I woke up and as a I stood in the shower, my foot was painful to stand on. On top of my right foot near my ankle, I could visibly see red inflammation in a vein. I massaged the vein and the redness and pain dissipated. Being fearful that I did have blood clots, I scheduled an appointment with a PA at my doctor?s office that same day. We discussed my ongoing dizziness, lightheadedness, and me being fearful of blood clots. She had an EKG performed at the office and ordered a barrage of blood tests. Everything continued to be normal. On Sunday, April 18th, I again went to the ER, because the hard vein in my stomach became larger and more tender to the touch. When I bent over, it felt like there was a lot of pressure emanating from the hard vein down to my groin. Once again, blood was drawn and everything was normal. I also had an ultrasound performed on the area that felt like a hard vein and the doctor concluded that it was most likely swollen lymph nodes. I was diagnosed with lymphadenopathy. On Monday, April 26th, I scheduled an appointment with my primary care doctor to discuss the ongoing dizziness, lightheadedness, and pain in my stomach and groin area. He told me that he had seen other patients that were experiencing similar symptoms and that my immune system was possibly overreacting to the vaccine. He told me the symptoms should go away in time. He also ordered a new blood test to check for clots. The D-Dimer test came back normal. On Tuesday, April 27th, I experienced a painful genital herpes outbreak. I normally get one every year. I had just recovered from an infection in December of 2020. This outbreak was more intense and for the first time I had nerve pain that wrapped around my hip and down my inner thigh. As of a week later, the infection is almost gone. Today is May 4th, and I am still experiencing dizziness and lightheadedness. Some days are better than others and every time I get optimistic that my dizziness and lightheadedness is finally gone, it reappears. Being an IT consultant business owner and an attorney, I need to think clearly for my profession. The side effects from the Moderna vaccine have made it very difficult to function. I would like to get fully vaccinated, but I am fearful of getting the second shot. I do not want the vaccine to cause permanent neurological damage or worse. Finally, I am sure your organization is aware, but there are many other people experiencing the same symptoms as me.

The headache, chills, nausea were initial symptoms. Within a week I became disoriented, forgetful, and had terrible headaches that led me to the Emergency Department. I was diagnosed with a Glioblastoma, clogged rear brain ventricles, and encephaly within 3 weeks of receiving the vaccine.
39 2021-06-15 decreased appetite Severe and erratic heartbeats, heavy slow breathing accompanied with severe fatigue, severe headache... Read more
Close
Severe and erratic heartbeats, heavy slow breathing accompanied with severe fatigue, severe headaches, and severe chills with no energy to move around for a week. After these symptoms eased, no appetite (went from eating five times a day and gym workouts 5 days a week to maybe eating twice a day and unable to walk up 20 stairs without shortness of breathe and heavy erratic heartbeats) still accompanied with little energy, erratic heartbeats, shortness of breath, and lingering headaches well into week three. Admitted myself to the ER on due to lingering affects and a new symptom of swelling/throbbing on the left side of my head; previous mentioned symptoms still there but milder than before. Diagnosis at ER was high blood pressure 150 over 92; never had blood pressure problems prior 1st COVID vaccine dose. Follow-up visit with primary care provider, checked my vitals and high blood pressure remained; primary care provider diagnosed high blood pressure, prescribed Amlodipine 5MG tablets.

Within the first 25 minutes, my arm went numb and my hand started swelling. I had a rapid heartbeat. I was nauseous, my blood pressure was elevated. They gave me a check up. I had paralysis in my left hand and was not able to move it. I was taken to the ER and had to do motion tests. I am able to move it now, but I have difficulty. I still have pain in my hand and arm.
